# Business Problem

## Predict customer charges for an insurance comapny based on given variables. 
## This will help the company to decide how much they charge people correctly


# Variables

## Age: age of primary beneficiary
## Sex: nsurance contractor gender, female, male
## BMI: body mass index, providing an understanding of teh body weights that are relatively high or low relative height,
##      an objective index of body weight(kg/m^2) using the ratio of height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9
## Children: number of children covered by health insurance/ number of dependents
## Smoking: smoking
## Region: the beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest and northwest
## Charges: idividual medical costs billed by health insurance

## Multivariate Analysis

# Correlation: 3 Types: Pearson, Kendall and Spearman
# We will combine the .corr() method with heatmap to see the (Pearson by default) correlations graphically
df_numeric = df.apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce').dropna(axis=1)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.heatmap(df_numeric.corr(), annot=True, square=True,
           cmap='RdBu',
           vmax=1,
           vmin=-1)
plt.title('Correlations Between Variables', size=18);
plt.xticks(size=13)
plt.yticks(size=13)
plt.show()

# We see that there is a positive correlation between age and insurance charges
# We also see that there is a weak correlation between BMI and charges
# Almost no relationship between children and charges.
